We must elect leaders who won't stand in the way of common sense efforts to make our communities safer from gun violence. We must do it for the people we lost in Uvalde. In Santa Fe. In Sutherland Springs. In Sandy Hook. And in cities across the country every day.
How do we do this? By electing people who will.

In Congress, I've co-sponsored & voted for legislation to address some of the violence. We can't do everything, but we can do everything in our power to help save a student, teacher, grocery shopper, concertgoer, or churchgoer‚Äôs life. The Senate must act & pass this legislation.

We cannot continue this way. We need lawmakers to dedicate themselves to ending the cycle of violence and being a part of the solution. We need Republicans to meet us in the middle on common-sense gun laws.

In Texas, we are hurting for the community of Uvalde. The senseless killing of children and those who tried to protect them takes us back, once again, to Santa Fe, to Sutherland Springs, to Sandy Hook.

And those elections are going on now. In 2022. We must vote as though our most cherished fundamental freedoms are at stake, as though our lives are at stake. They are.

And we can. The House has already voted to codify Roe in all 50 states, protecting the fundamental right to equality and participation in society it represents. But to see #WHPA become law, we have to win elections.

For as long as I can remember, people have warned that, given the chance, the Supreme Court would overturn Roe. If tonight‚Äôs report is true, that day is here.
